    "analysis": "What has been done: You computed global thresholds (P95/P5) for every component-KPI from the full series, then filtered metric data to the incident window (2022-03-21 05:00–05:30 UTC+8) and flagged per-point anomalies where value >= group_p95 OR value <= group_p5. You found 5,286 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups in-window. The top anomaly groups (by raw anomaly_count) are dominated by adservice KPIs where every point (31/31) was flagged because the series in-window is constant and equals the global p95/p5 (i.e., p95 == p5 == observed_value). This indicates many false positives due to compressed/constant global thresholds, so we must apply fault-identification heuristics to exclude such artifacts and keep only groups with significant deviation from thresholds. According to the failure diagnosis rules, faults should be consecutive anomalies with meaningful breach magnitude (e.g., >50% of extremal), and isolated small deviations or exact-equal-to-threshold constant series should be excluded.\n\nWhat can be derived: The raw anomaly counts alone are misleading; we need a severity metric to prioritize groups with real breaches (substantial increase or decrease relative to P95/P5). Next step should compute per-group severity (relative breach above p95 or below p5), require a minimum consecutive anomaly count, and list candidate faulty (component-KPI) groups that show both temporal continuity and breach >50% so we can narrow to real faults for subsequent trace/log analysis.",
